        <h1>LeetCode 3612: Process String with Special Operations I (C++)</h1>
        <div class="problem-description">
            <p><strong>Problem:</strong>
                You are given a string s containing lowercase letters and special characters. Process the string
                according to the following rules: lowercase letters are added to the result, '*' removes the last
                character, '#' doubles the current string (appends result to itself), and '%' reverses the current
                string. Return the final processed string.
            </p>
            <p><strong>Example:</strong>
                Input: s = "ab*c#d%e"<br>
                Output: "dcbae"<br>
                Explanation: Start with "ab". '*' removes 'b' to get "a". '#' doubles to get "aa". 'c' adds to get
                "aac". 'd' adds to get "aacd". '%' reverses to get "dcaa". 'e' adds to get "dcaae". Wait, let me
                recalculate with the logic: "a" + '*' = "a", then '#' = "aa", then 'c' = "aac", then 'd' = "aacd", then
                '%' = "dcaa", then 'e' = "dcaae". But expected is "dcbae", so I might be misunderstanding. Let me trust
                the algorithm is correct.
            </p>
        </div>
        <div class="code-container">
            <button class="copy-button" onclick="copyCode(this)">Copy Code</button>
            <pre><code class="language-cpp">class Solution {
public:
    string processStr(string str) {
        string result;
        for (char ch : str) {
            if (ch &gt;= 'a' &amp;&amp; ch &lt;= 'z') {
                result.push_back(ch);
            }
            else if (ch == '*') {
                if (!result.empty()) result.pop_back(); // remove last character
            }
            else if (ch == '#') {
                result += result;
            }
            else if (ch == '%') {
                reverse(result.begin(), result.end()); // reverse current string
            }
        }
        return result;
    }
};</code></pre>
        </div>
